Date: 31 Oct 2000 08:16:00 +0100
From: Robertson, Lucy <lucy.robertson@veths.no>
Source: Aftenposten on-line [edited

Man's death tied to Mad Cow Disease
------------------------------------
A Norwegian man who died last week at Aker Hospital in Oslo "most probably"
was suffering from the human form of mad cow disease or new variant
Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (nvCJD or vCJD). Doctors believe he was infected
while traveling overseas. The doctors claim there are no grounds for panic
since mad cow disease (Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy or BSE) has never
been detected in Norwegian meat. The chance of infection, they say, is very
low.
The man, thought to be Norway's first victim of the disease plaguing
Britain and France, was kept in isolation and the strongest
infection-control measures were put in place.
Doctors at Aker Hospital decline to reveal many details of the case but
it's believed the man was in his mid-50s and had been ill for at least
half-a-year. He traveled frequently abroad and may have eaten contaminated
meat while overseas.
­-
Robertson, Lucy
<lucy.robertson@veths.no>
